&#1506;&#1463;&#1491;-&#1497;&#1465;&#1488;&#1499;&#1463;&#1500;
&#1496;&#1462;&#1512;&#1462;&#1507;, &#1493;&#1456;&#1491;&#1463;&#1501;-&#1495;&#1458;&#1500;&#1464;&#1500;&#1460;&#1497;&#1501;
&#1497;&#1460;&#1513;&#1473;&#1456;&#1514;&#1468;&#1462;&#1492;</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:14.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b>They are a nation that like the Lion rises, and like the Lion lifts
up.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>He will not lie down until he has
eaten his prey. His victim's blood he drinks.<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>The Lion gets up to hunt.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>And
once he gets up, he won't get back down without making a kill. What aspect of
the Lion is being applied to <span class=SpellE>Benei</span> <span
class=SpellE>Yisrael</span>? <span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span><span
class=GramE>His power.</span> <span class=SpellE>Bilaam's</span> verse is a
threat to <span class=SpellE>Balak</span>.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span><st1:country-region w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Israel</st1:place></st1:country-region>
is on the prowl and won't stop until he has devoured <span class=SpellE>Balak's</span>
nation. <span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span>Like the <span class=GramE>Lion
,</span> <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region w:st="on">Israel</st1:country-region></st1:place>
cannot be stopped.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>In the <b>third</b> Blessing of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam</span>, also
in its last verse (24:9) the word <span class=SpellE>Lavi</span> again appears:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:David;
color:black'>&#1499;&#1468;&#1464;&#1512;&#1463;&#1506;
&#1513;&#1473;&#1464;&#1499;&#1463;&#1489;
&#1499;&#1468;&#1463;&#1488;&#1458;&#1512;&#1460;&#1497;
&#1493;&#1468;&#1499;&#1456;&#1500;&#1464;&#1489;&#1460;&#1497;&#1488;,
&#1502;&#1460;&#1497; &#1497;&#1456;&#1511;&#1460;&#1497;&#1502;&#1462;&#1504;&#1468;&#1493;&#1468;;</span></b><span
lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-family:David;color:black'><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>    </span>[[[</span><b><span lang=HE dir=RTL
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:David;color:black'>
&#1502;&#1456;&#1489;&#1464;&#1512;&#1456;&#1499;&#1462;&#1497;&#1498;&#1464;
&#1489;&#1464;&#1512;&#1493;&#1468;&#1498;&#1456;, <span class=SpellE>&#1493;&#1456;&#1488;&#1465;&#1512;&#1456;&#1512;&#1462;&#1497;</span>&#1498;&#1464;
&#1488;&#1464;&#1512;&#1493;&#1468;&#1512;</span></b><span lang=HE dir=RTL
style='font-family:David;color:black'>]]]</span><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b>Like a Lion he bends and lies down. Who can raise him up? </b>[[[<b>Those
who bless you are blessed. Those who curse you are cursed.</b>]]]<b><o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>[[[From the first Blessing of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam</span> we have a
similar language<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   </span>(verse 9) </p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span dir=RTL></span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-family:David;
color:black'><span dir=RTL></span><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>&#1492;&#1462;&#1503;-&#1506;&#1464;&#1501;
&#1500;&#1456;&#1489;&#1464;&#1491;&#1464;&#1491;
&#1497;&#1460;&#1513;&#1473;&#1456;&#1499;&#1468;&#1465;&#1503;, <span
class=SpellE>&#1493;&#1468;&#1489;&#1463;&#1490;&#1468;</span>&#1493;&#1465;&#1497;&#1460;&#1501;
&#1500;&#1465;&#1488;
&#1497;&#1460;&#1514;&#1456;&#1495;&#1463;&#1513;&#1468;&#1473;&#1464;&#1489;</span><span
dir=LTR></span><span dir=LTR></span> This verse then is taken to mean that
Israel sits alone and no one interferes with him or tries to remove him from
his land.]]]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>In this blessing of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam</span> there is also a
depiction of the Lion's strength, but in another way. After the kill, once the
Lion is settled down, who can raise him up again?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Once <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region
 w:st="on">Israel</st1:country-region></st1:place> has settled in the land, no
nation can remove them.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This of course
also serves as a warning to <span class=SpellE>Balak</span>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span class=SpellE>Benei</span> <st1:country-region w:st="on"><st1:place
 w:st="on">Israel</st1:place></st1:country-region> <span class=GramE>are</span>
compared to the Lion in the Lion's capacity to beat all foes and to take the
land he desires, never to be displaced.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   
</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>The blessing Yaakov gives to <span class=SpellE>Yehudah</span> also contains
these two aspects of the two blessings of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam</span>:<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>of going up and fighting, and of settling
down with no chance to be moved.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Only the
order is a bit different, but the meaning is the same. <span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span>Yaakov is blessing <span class=SpellE>Yehudah</span>,
that his descendents, whether it <span class=GramE>be</span> all of <st1:country-region
w:st="on">Israel</st1:country-region>, David, or <span class=SpellE>Mashiach</span>,
will, in the future conquer and keep the <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:PlaceType
 w:st="on">Land</st1:PlaceType> of <st1:PlaceName w:st="on">Israel</st1:PlaceName></st1:place>.
Yaakov's blessing to <span class=SpellE>Yehudah</span> is a precursor to the
eventual clear blessing of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam</span> to <span
class=SpellE>Benei</span> <span class=SpellE>Yisrael</span>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   </span>Perhaps Yaakov intentionally altered the
blessing so as to hide the meaning of the prophecy until the time of <span
class=SpellE>Bilaam</span>.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>We also learn from the equivalency of the two blessings that a verse
which ostensibly refers to <span class=SpellE><span class=GramE>Yehudah</span></span><span
class=GramE>,</span> can also be understood as applying to all of <st1:country-region
w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Israel</st1:place></st1:country-region>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This makes sense since we know that <span
class=SpellE>Yehudah</span> is destined to be the name given to all of <span
class=SpellE>Benei</span> <st1:place w:st="on"><st1:country-region w:st="on">Israel</st1:country-region></st1:place>
as we see with <span class=SpellE>Mordechai</span> who although being from the
tribe of Benjamin was called:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt'>&#1488;&#1497;&#1513;
&#1497;&#1492;&#1493;&#1491;&#1497;</span></b><span dir=LTR></span><span
lang=HE style='font-size:14.0pt'><span dir=LTR></span> <span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span></span><b>A man of <span class=SpellE>Yehudah</span></b>.<b><span
style='font-size:14.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>The Lion and Judah are connected in another unexpected way.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span><span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> <span
class=SpellE>ben</span> <span class=SpellE>Teima</span> is quoted at the very
end of <span class=SpellE>Pirke</span> <span class=SpellE>Avot</span> in the <span
class=SpellE>Mishna</span> as telling his students to be as the Lion in serving
G-d.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>[[<span class=GramE>[ Interestingly</span>,
<span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> Ben <span class=SpellE>Taima</span> in this
same place also provides the only<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>example of a prayer given in the <span class=SpellE>Mishna</span>. ]]]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:David;
color:black'>&#1497;&#1492;&#1493;&#1491;&#1492; &#1489;&#1503; <span
class=SpellE>&#1514;&#1497;&#1502;&#1488;</span> &#1488;&#1493;&#1502;&#1512;,
&#1492;&#1493;&#1497; &#1506;&#1494; &#1499;&#1504;&#1502;&#1512;,
&#1493;&#1511;&#1500; &#1499;&#1504;&#1513;&#1512;, &#1493;&#1512;&#1509;
&#1499;&#1510;&#1489;&#1497;, &#1493;&#1490;&#1497;&#1489;&#1493;&#1512;
&#1499;&#1488;&#1512;&#1497;--&#1500;&#1506;&#1513;&#1493;&#1514;
&#1512;&#1510;&#1493;&#1503; &#1488;&#1489;&#1497;&#1498;
&#1513;&#1489;&#1513;&#1502;&#1497;&#1497;&#1501;.&nbsp; &#1492;&#1493;&#1488;
&#1492;&#1497;&#1492; &#1488;&#1493;&#1502;&#1512;, &#1506;&#1494;
&#1508;&#1504;&#1497;&#1501; <span class=SpellE>&#1500;&#1490;&#1497;&#1492;&#1497;&#1504;&#1501;</span>,
&#1493;&#1489;&#1493;&#1513; &#1508;&#1504;&#1497;&#1501; &#1500;&#1490;&#1503;
&#1506;&#1491;&#1503;.&nbsp; &#1499;&#1503; &#1497;&#1492;&#1497;
&#1512;&#1510;&#1493;&#1503; &#1502;&#1500;&#1508;&#1504;&#1497;&#1498;
&#1492;' &#1488;&#1500;&#1493;&#1492;&#1497;&#1504;&#1493;
&#1513;&#1514;&#1497;&#1489;&#1504;&#1492; &#1506;&#1497;&#1512;&#1498;
&#1489;&#1497;&#1502;&#1497;&#1504;&#1493;, &#1493;&#1514;&#1497;&#1514;&#1503;
&#1495;&#1500;&#1511;&#1504;&#1493; &#1489;&#1514;&#1493;&#1512;&#1514;&#1498;,
&#1493;&#1506;&#1501; &#1506;&#1493;&#1513;&#1497;
&#1512;&#1510;&#1493;&#1504;&#1498;.</span></b><span dir=LTR></span><b><span
lang=HE style='font-size:14.0pt'><span dir=LTR></span> </span><span
class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> <span class=SpellE>ben</span> <span class=SpellE>Teima</span>
says: be bold as a leopard, light as an eagle, fast as a deer and powerful as a
lion to do the will of your Father in heaven.<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> Ben <span class=SpellE>Teima</span>
transforms the comparison of <st1:country-region w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Israel</st1:place></st1:country-region>
to a Lion from the militaristic sphere to the personal, internal sphere.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Like a Lion overpowers his prey, we must
overpower our own reluctances to do G-<span class=SpellE>d's</span> will.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   </span>This redefinition of what we can learn from
the Lion has particular meaning when we realize <span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span>
Ben <span class=SpellE>Teima</span> is living in a time when <st1:country-region
w:st="on">Israel</st1:country-region> has been removed from their land after
hundreds of years by the <st1:place w:st="on">Roman Empire</st1:place>. So he
reinterprets the prophetic meaning of <span class=SpellE>Bilaam's</span>
Blessing into a sphere where every person can still be mighty, in his battles
with his own character flaws. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'>The <span class=SpellE>Shulchan</span> <span class=SpellE>Aruch</span>
adopts and modifies <span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> Ben <span class=SpellE>Teima's</span>
teaching and uses it as the introduction to his work.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span dir=RTL></span><b><i><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'><span dir=RTL></span>.</span></i></b><b><span
lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:
Narkisim'> &#1497;&#1514;&#1490;&#1489;&#1512; &#1499;&#1488;&#1512;&#1497;
&#1500;&#1506;&#1502;&#1493;&#1491; &#1489;&#1489;&#1493;&#1511;&#1512;
&#1500;&#1506;&#1489;&#1493;&#1491;&#1514; &#1489;&#1493;&#1512;&#1488;&#1493;,
&#1513;&#1497;&#1492;&#1488; &#1492;&#1493;&#1488;
&#1502;&#1506;&#1493;&#1512;&#1512; &#1492;&#1513;&#1495;&#1512;</span></b><b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><b><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>Be
empowered like a lion to rise in the morning for the service of one's <span
class=GramE>Creator, that</span> he should wake up [before] the dawn.<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>[[[Interestingly,
here the <span class=SpellE>Kitzur</span> <span class=SpellE>Shulchan</span> <span
class=SpellE><span class=GramE>Aruch</span></span><span class=GramE><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>is</span> longer than the original.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>He restates the full teaching of <span
class=SpellE>Yehudah</span> <span class=SpellE>ben</span> <span class=SpellE>Teima</span>
and elaborates on <span class=GramE>it .</span><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>]]]<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>The
<span class=SpellE>Shulchan</span> <span class=SpellE>Aruch</span> takes this
teaching in a <span class=SpellE>Halachic</span> direction: How must one
conquer himself? <span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>    </span>By getting up early
in the morning to pray, and not being lazy.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>Being </span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1512;&#1497;&#1494;</span><span dir=LTR></span><span
style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span>
<span class=GramE>[ prompt</span> ] in serving G-d is thus the lesson the lion
teaches us, whether or not the lion as we see him in the Zoo is exactly the
epitome of </span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1512;&#1497;&#1494;</span><span dir=LTR></span><span
style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>Our
Little <span class=SpellE>Lavi</span> <span class=SpellE>Yehudah</span> is
certainly </span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1512;&#1497;&#1494;</span><span dir=LTR></span><span
style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span>.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   </span>Not only was he born slightly before
schedule, but he was also </span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1512;&#1497;&#1494;</span><span
dir=LTR></span><span lang=HE style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:
Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span> </span><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>in the actual labor.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>The Doctor at our first hospital was worried
that he would take too long and wanted to give Lena a </span><span lang=HE
dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1497;&#1512;&#1493;&#1494;</span><span
dir=LTR></span><span lang=HE style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:
Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span> </span><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'>[ inducement ] but after leaving that hospital
and finally arriving at <span class=SpellE>Bikur</span> <span class=SpellE>Holim</span>,
it seemed we did not need a </span><span lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;
mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1497;&#1512;&#1493;&#1494;</span><span
dir=LTR></span><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:
Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span> , little<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span><span class=SpellE>Lavi</span> <span class=SpellE>Yehuda</span> was </span><span
lang=HE dir=RTL style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:
Narkisim'>&#1494;&#1512;&#1497;&#1494;</span><span dir=LTR></span><span
style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><span dir=LTR></span>
all on his own.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>And since he was born he
has taken on another aspect of the lion, he slumbers very well.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal dir=LTR style='text-align:left;direction:ltr;unicode-bidi:
embed'><span style='mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Narkisim'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

